{"id":"2304.03063","submitter":"Neri Merhav","authors":"Neri Merhav","title":"Some families of Jensen-like inequalities with application to\n  information theory","comments":"20 pages, 4 figures, submitted for publication","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3390/e25050752","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is well known that the traditional Jensen inequality is proved by lower\nbounding the given convex function, $f(x)$, by the tangential affine function\nthat passes through the point $(E\\{X\\},f(E\\{X\\}))$, where $E\\{X\\}$ is the\nexpectation of the random variable $X$. While this tangential affine function\nyields the tightest lower bound among all lower bounds induced by affine\nfunctions that are tangential to $f$, it turns out that when the function $f$\nis just part of a more complicated expression whose expectation is to be\nbounded, the tightest lower bound might belong to a tangential affine function\nthat passes through a point different than $(E\\{X\\},f(E\\{X\\}))$. In this paper,\nwe take advantage of this observation, by optimizing the point of tangency with\nregard to the specific given expression, in a variety of cases, and thereby\nderive several families of inequalities, henceforth referred to as\n``Jensen-like'' inequalities, which are new to the best knowledge of the\nauthor. The degree of tightness and the potential usefulness of these\ninequalities is demonstrated in several application examples related to\ninformation theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Apr 2023 13:28:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-17"}
